04368nam a22007095i 9780520967557DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20172017cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2017039458  a97805209675577 a10.1525/97805209675572doi  a(DE-B1597)521148  a(OCoLC)1004984283  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aQC902.9 7aHIS0540002bisacsh1 aStreeby, Shelley, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImagining the Future of Climate Change :bWorld-Making through Science Fiction and Activism /cShelley Streeby. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (168 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Studies Now: Critical Histories of the Present ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tOverview -- tIntroduction. Imagining the Future of Climate Change -- t1. #NoDAPL. Native American and Indigenous Science, Fiction, and Futurisms -- t2. Climate Refugees in the Greenhouse World. Archiving Global Warming with Octavia E. Butler -- t3. Climate Change as a World Problem. Shaping Change in the Wake of Disaster -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tKey Figures -- tSelected Bibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the 1960s to the present, activists, artists, and science fiction writers have imagined the consequences of climate change and its impacts on our future. Authors such as Octavia Butler and Leslie Marmon Silko, movie directors such as Bong Joon-Ho, and creators of digital media such as the makers of the Maori web series Anamata Future News have all envisioned future worlds during and after environmental collapse, engaging audiences to think about the earth’s sustainability. As public awareness of climate change has grown, so has the popularity of works of climate fiction that connect science with activism. Today, real-world social movements helmed by Indigenous people and people of color are leading the way against the greatest threat to our environment: the fossil fuel industry. Their stories and movements—in the real world and through science fiction—help us all better understand the relationship between activism and culture, and how both can be valuable tools in creating our future. Imagining the Future of Climate Change introduces readers to the history and most significant flashpoints in climate justice through speculative fictions and social movements, exploring post-disaster possibilities and the art of world-making.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aClimatic changes. 0aEthnoecologyzUnited States. 0aGlobal warming. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEcologyzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  abiologist.  aclimate change.  aclimate justice.  adigital media.  aecologist.  aimpact of global warming.  amarine biologist.  apreservation.  ascience fiction.  asustainability.  asustainable lifestyle.  awhat happens during climate change.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052029445540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096755740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520967557423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520967557/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles